    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Here is a simple example demonstrating vectorization with numpy"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "8tAatmNlnNuB"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "W-X5LyQS8uc7"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import time\n",
        "\n",
        "arr = np.arange(1_000_000)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Loop\n",
        "%time loop_res = [x * 2 for x in arr]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Vectorized\n",
        "%time vec_res = arr * 2\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Here is a slightly more complex function. Compare the timing of the 3 solutions."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "VIilLGabvmNp"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Loop\n",
        "%time loop_res = [x ** 2 + 2*x + 1 for x in arr]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Vectorized\n",
        "\n",
        "%time vec_res1 = arr**2+2*arr + 1\n",
        "\n",
        "# Vectorized using custom function\n",
        "vec = np.vectorize(lambda x: x**2 + 2*x + 1)\n",
        "%time vec_res2 = vec(arr)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "mHmatxEr841b"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "To take advantage of vectorization, we often need to use numpy's broadcasting. This is an example of broadcasting 2 arrays which will **not** work."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9tCYUXJovthB"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "arr_a = np.random.rand(3,4,6,2) # random array of shape (3,4,6,2)\n",
        "arr_b = np.random.rand(3, 5, 1, 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "arr_a + arr_b   # op throws an error"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "yn4mpsDeAb5J"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "This is an example of broadcasting 2 arrays which **will** work."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Z4bA2dHMv249"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "arr_a = np.random.rand(3,4,6,2) # random array of shape (3,4,6,2)\n",
        "arr_b = np.random.rand(3, 4, 1, 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "arr_a + arr_b   # op goes through without throwing an error."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "by-zV_xVRRc3"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "We can use broadcasting to accelerate more complex operations in python. In the following example, we want to calculate arr1*arr2"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "SfHdFqEowFus"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "%%timeit\n",
        "sum  = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "arr1 = np.array([1, 2, 3])\n",
        "arr2 = np.array([4, 5])\n",
        "\n",
        "for i in arr1:\n",
        "  for j in arr2:\n",
        "    sum += i*j"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JN-s7s4Dhowb"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
